/* CCSP :: content/pbqs.js — CCSP performance-based question database (30). */
window.CCSP = window.CCSP || {}; CCSP.pbqs = CCSP.pbqs || [];
CCSP.pbqs.push.apply(CCSP.pbqs, [{"id":"PBQ-01","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1.2","title":"Map the Service Category to the Capability","brief":"A cloud advisor is documenting three prospective services for an enterprise portfolio. For each, identify the NIST service category the customer is consuming.","exhibitTitle":"SERVICE INTAKE — capability description","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>CANDIDATE A</span>  Vendor delivers a finished email + calendar suite.\n           Customer only configures policy and users; no OS access.\n\n<span class='cy'>CANDIDATE B</span>  Vendor exposes runtime, libraries, and a managed\n           database. Customer <span class='hl'>deploys its own application code</span>\n           but cannot patch the underlying OS.\n\n<span class='cy'>CANDIDATE C</span>  Vendor provisions <span class='hl'>virtual machines, block storage,\n           and virtual networks</span>. Customer installs and patches the\n           guest OS, middleware, and everything above.\n\n<span class='dim'>NIST SP 800-145 service categories: SaaS, PaaS, IaaS</span>","fields":[{"label":"Candidate A is best classified as:","hint":"Consumer only configures; no infrastructure or runtime control.","options":["SaaS","PaaS","IaaS"],"answer":0,"explain":"SaaS is correct: the consumer uses a finished application (email/calendar) and controls only limited app-level configuration, exactly the NIST SP 800-145 SaaS definition. PaaS is wrong because there is no customer-deployed code or runtime here. IaaS is wrong because the customer gets no VMs, storage, or network to manage."},{"label":"Candidate B is best classified as:","hint":"Customer deploys code but does not touch the OS.","options":["SaaS","PaaS","IaaS"],"answer":1,"explain":"PaaS is correct: the consumer deploys its own application onto a vendor-managed platform (runtime, libraries, managed DB) without controlling the OS or hardware. SaaS is wrong because the customer runs custom code rather than a finished app. IaaS is wrong because the customer cannot patch or manage the underlying OS."},{"label":"Candidate C is best classified as:","hint":"Customer manages the guest OS and up.","options":["SaaS","PaaS","IaaS"],"answer":2,"explain":"IaaS is correct: the consumer receives fundamental compute, storage, and networking and manages the guest OS, middleware, and applications — the NIST IaaS boundary. SaaS is wrong because no finished application is delivered. PaaS is wrong because the customer manages the OS, which a PaaS platform abstracts away."},{"label":"Across A→B→C, the volume of security responsibility the CUSTOMER retains generally:","hint":"Think about how much of the stack the customer manages.","options":["Decreases","Increases","Stays identical in all three"],"answer":1,"explain":"Increases is correct: moving SaaS→PaaS→IaaS pushes more of the stack (runtime, OS, patching) to the customer, so customer responsibility grows. Decreases is the reverse of reality. Stays identical is wrong because the responsibility line demonstrably shifts with each model."}],"summary":"SaaS = finished app (config only), PaaS = customer code on a managed platform, IaaS = customer-managed OS on vendor compute. Customer security responsibility grows as you move from SaaS toward IaaS."},{"id":"PBQ-02","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1.4","title":"Draw the Shared-Responsibility Line","brief":"For an IaaS deployment, assign each control task to the party that owns it under the shared-responsibility model.","exhibitTitle":"IaaS RESPONSIBILITY WORKSHEET","exhibit":"DEPLOYMENT: IaaS — customer runs guest OS + apps on vendor VMs\n\n<span class='cy'>TASK 1</span>  Physically destroy failed drives in the data center\n<span class='cy'>TASK 2</span>  Patch the guest operating system on each VM\n<span class='cy'>TASK 3</span>  Configure the network security group / firewall rules\n<span class='cy'>TASK 4</span>  Secure and patch the <span class='hl'>hypervisor</span> host\n\n<span class='dim'>Parties: Cloud Service Provider (CSP)  |  Cloud Customer</span>","fields":[{"label":"TASK 1 — Physical destruction of failed drives is owned by:","hint":"Who controls the physical facility?","options":["Cloud Customer","Cloud Service Provider","Shared 50/50"],"answer":1,"explain":"The CSP is correct: physical facility and media handling always belong to the provider in every cloud model. Cloud Customer is wrong because the customer never has physical access to CSP hardware. Shared 50/50 is wrong — physical security is wholly the provider's, not a split control."},{"label":"TASK 2 — Patching the guest OS on each VM is owned by:","hint":"In IaaS, who owns the guest OS?","options":["Cloud Service Provider","Cloud Customer","Neither — it auto-patches"],"answer":1,"explain":"The Cloud Customer is correct: in IaaS the guest OS is squarely the customer's responsibility, including patching. CSP is wrong because the provider only manages up to the hypervisor in IaaS. 'Neither/auto-patches' is wrong — IaaS guest OS patching is not performed by the platform automatically."},{"label":"TASK 3 — Configuring network security group / firewall rules is owned by:","hint":"Who defines which traffic reaches the VMs?","options":["Cloud Customer","Cloud Service Provider","The regulator"],"answer":0,"explain":"The Cloud Customer is correct: the provider supplies the security-group capability, but configuring the actual allow/deny rules is the customer's control decision. CSP is wrong because the provider offers the tool, not the tenant-specific policy. The regulator is wrong — regulators set requirements, they do not configure controls."},{"label":"TASK 4 — Securing and patching the hypervisor is owned by:","hint":"The hypervisor sits below the guest OS.","options":["Cloud Customer","Cloud Service Provider","Shared with the customer"],"answer":1,"explain":"The CSP is correct: the hypervisor and everything beneath it is always the provider's responsibility, even in IaaS. Cloud Customer is wrong because tenants have no access to the hypervisor layer. Shared is wrong — the customer cannot touch the hypervisor, so it cannot be a shared control."}],"summary":"In IaaS the provider owns physical, hypervisor, and infrastructure; the customer owns guest OS, patching, and network/security-group configuration. Physical and hypervisor duties are never shared with the tenant."},{"id":"PBQ-03","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1.2","title":"Select the Right Deployment Model","brief":"A cloud architect must match each business scenario to the NIST deployment model that best fits its stated constraints.","exhibitTitle":"DEPLOYMENT-MODEL SCENARIOS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SCENARIO 1</span>  Five regional hospitals want a shared, restricted\n            cloud governed by common HIPAA/HITECH requirements,\n            <span class='hl'>not open to the general public</span>.\n\n<span class='cy'>SCENARIO 2</span>  A retailer keeps sensitive card data on a private\n            cloud but <span class='hl'>bursts web front-ends to a public cloud</span>\n            during seasonal peaks, with orchestration between them.\n\n<span class='cy'>SCENARIO 3</span>  A startup wants the lowest cost and fastest scale,\n            accepts multi-tenant infrastructure, and has no\n            special isolation mandate.\n\n<span class='dim'>Models: Public, Private, Community, Hybrid, Multi-cloud</span>","fields":[{"label":"SCENARIO 1 best fits which model?","hint":"Shared by organizations with a common concern.","options":["Public cloud","Community cloud","Private cloud"],"answer":1,"explain":"Community cloud is correct: NIST defines it as infrastructure shared by several organizations with a common concern (here, HIPAA-regulated hospitals). Public is wrong because it is expressly not open to the general public. Private is wrong because it is shared across multiple independent organizations, not dedicated to one."},{"label":"SCENARIO 2 best fits which model?","hint":"Private core plus public burst, orchestrated together.","options":["Hybrid cloud","Community cloud","Public cloud"],"answer":0,"explain":"Hybrid cloud is correct: it composes distinct private and public clouds bound by technology enabling data/app portability (cloud bursting). Community is wrong because this is one org, not several with a shared concern. Public alone is wrong because the sensitive card data stays on a private cloud."},{"label":"SCENARIO 3 best fits which model?","hint":"Cheapest, multi-tenant, no isolation mandate.","options":["Private cloud","Public cloud","Hybrid cloud"],"answer":1,"explain":"Public cloud is correct: lowest cost and fastest elasticity on shared multi-tenant infrastructure, with no isolation requirement. Private is wrong because dedicated infrastructure raises cost without a stated need. Hybrid is wrong because there is no private component or bursting requirement described."},{"label":"The retailer in Scenario 2 later adds a SECOND independent public provider for resilience. This addition is best described as:","hint":"More than one public provider used together.","options":["Multi-cloud","Community cloud","Reverting to private cloud"],"answer":0,"explain":"Multi-cloud is correct: using two or more distinct public providers together is the multi-cloud pattern, often for resilience or avoiding lock-in. Community is wrong because it concerns shared-concern organizations, not multiple providers. Reverting to private is wrong — adding a public provider does not remove the public tier."}],"summary":"Community = shared-concern orgs; Hybrid = bound private+public with bursting; Public = cheap multi-tenant; Multi-cloud = two or more public providers used together."},{"id":"PBQ-04","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1.4","title":"Apply Secure Cloud Design Principles","brief":"An architect is reviewing design decisions against secure-cloud design principles. Choose the principle or requirement each decision addresses.","exhibitTitle":"DESIGN DECISION LOG","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>DECISION 1</span>  Store data in an <span class='hl'>open, standard format</span> and keep\n            an export path so workloads can move to another\n            provider without rewrite.\n\n<span class='cy'>DECISION 2</span>  Require the contract to include a clean data\n            <span class='hl'>extraction + deletion</span> process at end of service so the\n            customer can fully exit the provider.\n\n<span class='cy'>DECISION 3</span>  Two systems from different providers must exchange\n            data using a common API/schema <span class='hl'>without custom glue</span>.\n\n<span class='cy'>DECISION 4</span>  Encrypt data before it enters the cloud and keep\n            keys in a customer-controlled HSM.\n\n<span class='dim'>Concepts: portability, interoperability, reversibility, vendor lock-in, customer-managed keys</span>","fields":[{"label":"DECISION 1 primarily supports:","hint":"Moving workloads between providers.","options":["Interoperability","Portability","Reversibility"],"answer":1,"explain":"Portability is correct: standard formats and export paths let workloads/data move between providers with minimal rework. Interoperability is wrong because that concerns systems working together, not relocation. Reversibility is wrong because it specifically covers cleanly exiting a provider, addressed by Decision 2."},{"label":"DECISION 2 primarily supports:","hint":"The ability to cleanly exit a provider.","options":["Reversibility","Portability","Elasticity"],"answer":0,"explain":"Reversibility is correct: the ability to remove all data and terminate service cleanly is the definition of reversibility. Portability is wrong because it concerns moving to another provider, not exiting. Elasticity is wrong — that is dynamic scaling, unrelated to exit and deletion."},{"label":"DECISION 3 primarily supports:","hint":"Different systems working together.","options":["Reversibility","Interoperability","Multi-tenancy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Interoperability is correct: common APIs/schemas let systems from different providers exchange data without custom integration. Reversibility is wrong because that concerns exiting a provider. Multi-tenancy is wrong — it describes shared infrastructure, not cross-system data exchange."},{"label":"DECISION 4 most directly reduces the risk of:","hint":"Provider holding both data and keys.","options":["Vendor lock-in on compute","Provider access to plaintext / key custody risk","Network latency"],"answer":1,"explain":"Provider access to plaintext / key custody risk is correct: customer-held keys mean the provider cannot read plaintext, preserving customer control. Vendor lock-in on compute is wrong because key custody is about confidentiality, not compute portability. Network latency is wrong — encryption and key location do not address latency."}],"summary":"Portability = move between providers; reversibility = clean exit; interoperability = systems work together; customer-managed keys keep the provider out of plaintext."},{"id":"PBQ-05","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1.4","title":"Shift the Responsibility Line Across Models","brief":"One organization runs the same control tasks under SaaS, PaaS, and IaaS. Decide who owns each task in the specified model.","exhibitTitle":"CROSS-MODEL RESPONSIBILITY MATRIX","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ROW A</span>  Application-layer access control / user roles\n        Model in question: <span class='hl'>SaaS</span>\n\n<span class='cy'>ROW B</span>  Middleware and runtime patching\n        Model in question: <span class='hl'>PaaS</span>\n\n<span class='cy'>ROW C</span>  Guest OS hardening and baseline\n        Model in question: <span class='hl'>IaaS</span>\n\n<span class='cy'>ROW D</span>  Data classification & who may access the data\n        Model in question: <span class='hl'>ANY model</span>\n\n<span class='dim'>Owners: Provider only  |  Customer only  |  Provider (customer configures)</span>","fields":[{"label":"ROW A (SaaS) — application-layer access control / user roles is owned by:","hint":"Even in SaaS, who decides who gets access?","options":["Provider only","Customer (configures identities/roles)","Nobody — it is open by default"],"answer":1,"explain":"Customer is correct: even in SaaS, the customer manages its own identities, roles, and access grants within the app. Provider only is wrong because the provider supplies the app but not the tenant's user decisions. 'Nobody/open by default' is wrong — access is governed, not open."},{"label":"ROW B (PaaS) — middleware and runtime patching is owned by:","hint":"In PaaS, who manages the runtime layer?","options":["Customer only","Provider","The end user"],"answer":1,"explain":"Provider is correct: in PaaS the platform (runtime, middleware) is managed and patched by the provider. Customer only is wrong because the customer manages its code, not the runtime. The end user is wrong — end users consume the app and never patch middleware."},{"label":"ROW C (IaaS) — guest OS hardening and baseline is owned by:","hint":"IaaS guest OS boundary.","options":["Provider","Customer","Shared equally"],"answer":1,"explain":"Customer is correct: in IaaS the guest OS, including hardening and baselines, belongs to the customer. Provider is wrong because the provider stops at the hypervisor. Shared equally is wrong — the guest OS is wholly the tenant's responsibility in IaaS."},{"label":"ROW D — data classification and data-access decisions are owned by:","hint":"This one does not change with the service model.","options":["Provider only","Customer in every model","Only in IaaS"],"answer":1,"explain":"Customer in every model is correct: the data owner (customer) always retains responsibility for classifying data and deciding access, regardless of SaaS/PaaS/IaaS. Provider only is wrong because the provider is a custodian, not the data owner. 'Only in IaaS' is wrong — data ownership does not shift with the model."}],"summary":"Access decisions and data classification stay with the customer in every model; middleware/runtime is the provider's in PaaS; the guest OS is the customer's in IaaS."},{"id":"PBQ-06","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1.2","title":"Choose the Cloud Role for Each Actor","brief":"Map each actor in a cloud engagement to its NIST/CSA cloud-computing role.","exhibitTitle":"CLOUD ENGAGEMENT — actor descriptions","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ACTOR 1</span>  Operates the physical infrastructure and delivers\n         the cloud service to tenants.\n\n<span class='cy'>ACTOR 2</span>  A firm that <span class='hl'>aggregates and intermediates</span> several\n         cloud services, adding value and a single point of\n         contact for the customer.\n\n<span class='cy'>ACTOR 3</span>  An independent party engaged to <span class='hl'>assess and attest</span>\n         to the provider's controls (e.g., a SOC 2 examination).\n\n<span class='cy'>ACTOR 4</span>  The organization that consumes the service and\n         remains the data owner.\n\n<span class='dim'>Roles: cloud provider, cloud customer, cloud broker, cloud auditor, regulator</span>","fields":[{"label":"ACTOR 1 is the:","hint":"Delivers the service, runs the infrastructure.","options":["Cloud broker","Cloud service provider","Cloud auditor"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cloud service provider is correct: it operates infrastructure and delivers the service to tenants. Cloud broker is wrong because a broker intermediates services rather than operating the infrastructure. Cloud auditor is wrong — auditors assess controls, they do not deliver the service."},{"label":"ACTOR 2 is the:","hint":"Intermediates and aggregates multiple services.","options":["Cloud broker","Cloud provider","Regulator"],"answer":0,"explain":"Cloud broker is correct: it aggregates, intermediates, and adds value across multiple services as a single contact. Cloud provider is wrong because the broker does not operate the underlying infrastructure. Regulator is wrong — a regulator sets rules, it does not broker services."},{"label":"ACTOR 3 is the:","hint":"Independent assessment and attestation.","options":["Cloud customer","Cloud auditor","Cloud broker"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cloud auditor is correct: an independent party that assesses and attests to controls (e.g., SOC 2). Cloud customer is wrong because the customer consumes the service, it does not perform the independent attestation. Cloud broker is wrong — brokering is intermediation, not attestation."},{"label":"ACTOR 4 is the:","hint":"Consumes the service; remains the data owner.","options":["Cloud customer","Cloud provider","Cloud auditor"],"answer":0,"explain":"Cloud customer is correct: the consuming organization is the cloud customer and remains the data owner. Cloud provider is wrong because the provider delivers, not consumes, the service. Cloud auditor is wrong — the auditor assesses controls rather than consuming the service as data owner."}],"summary":"Provider operates and delivers; broker intermediates/aggregates; auditor independently attests; customer consumes and stays the data owner."},{"id":"PBQ-07","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2.1","title":"Order and Identify the Cloud Data Lifecycle","brief":"Given a set of activities, identify which phase of the cloud secure data lifecycle each belongs to.","exhibitTitle":"DATA LIFECYCLE — activity log","exhibit":"NIST/CSA cloud secure data lifecycle:\n  <span class='cy'>Create -> Store -> Use -> Share -> Archive -> Destroy</span>\n\n<span class='hl'>ACT 1</span>  New records are generated by an application and\n        first written to primary object storage.\n<span class='hl'>ACT 2</span>  Records are moved to cold, long-term retention\n        storage for the 7-year regulatory hold.\n<span class='hl'>ACT 3</span>  A copy is transmitted to an external business\n        partner over a secured channel.\n<span class='hl'>ACT 4</span>  Records past retention are crypto-shredded so the\n        data is unrecoverable.","fields":[{"label":"ACT 1 belongs to which lifecycle phase?","hint":"New data first written.","options":["Store","Create","Use"],"answer":1,"explain":"Create is correct: generating new data and first committing it is the Create phase (the initial write is treated as part of Create/Store transition, but generation is Create). Store is wrong because storage of already-created data is a distinct following phase and this describes generation. Use is wrong — no processing/consumption is occurring yet."},{"label":"ACT 2 belongs to which lifecycle phase?","hint":"Cold, long-term retention.","options":["Store","Archive","Destroy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Archive is correct: moving data to long-term, cold retention is the Archive phase. Store is wrong because Store is active/primary storage, not the cold retention tier. Destroy is wrong — the data is retained, not eliminated."},{"label":"ACT 3 belongs to which lifecycle phase?","hint":"Data leaves the organization to a partner.","options":["Use","Share","Archive"],"answer":1,"explain":"Share is correct: transmitting data to an external party is the Share phase. Use is wrong because Use is internal processing/consumption, not external exchange. Archive is wrong — nothing is being moved to cold retention."},{"label":"ACT 4 belongs to which lifecycle phase?","hint":"Rendering data unrecoverable.","options":["Archive","Destroy","Store"],"answer":1,"explain":"Destroy is correct: crypto-shredding to make data unrecoverable is the Destroy phase. Archive is wrong because archiving retains data rather than eliminating it. Store is wrong — Store keeps data available, the opposite of destruction."}],"summary":"Create (generate) → Store (primary) → Use (process) → Share (external) → Archive (cold retention) → Destroy (crypto-shred). Cold retention is Archive, not Store; external transmission is Share, not Use."},{"id":"PBQ-08","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2.3","title":"Match the Data-Protection Technique","brief":"For each protection requirement, select the technique that best satisfies it.","exhibitTitle":"PROTECTION REQUIREMENTS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQ 1</span>  Replace a primary account number (PAN) with a\n        <span class='hl'>surrogate value</span>; the mapping is held in a secure\n        vault so the original can be retrieved by authorized\n        systems. Reduces PCI DSS scope.\n\n<span class='cy'>REQ 2</span>  In a developer test dataset, permanently replace real\n        names/SSNs with realistic <span class='hl'>fake but format-preserving</span>\n        values; originals are NOT recoverable from the masked set.\n\n<span class='cy'>REQ 3</span>  Protect data at rest so that only holders of the key\n        can render plaintext; fully <span class='hl'>reversible with the key</span>.\n\n<span class='cy'>REQ 4</span>  Produce a fixed-length fingerprint to verify integrity;\n        the original cannot be recovered from the output.\n\n<span class='dim'>Techniques: tokenization, static data masking, encryption, hashing</span>","fields":[{"label":"REQ 1 is best met by:","hint":"Surrogate value with a reversible vault mapping; PCI-scope reduction.","options":["Encryption","Tokenization","Hashing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tokenization is correct: a surrogate token replaces the PAN with the mapping held in a vault, reducing PCI scope. Encryption is wrong because it transforms data mathematically with a key rather than substituting a vault-mapped token, and it does not reduce PCI scope the same way. Hashing is wrong — it is one-way and cannot return the original PAN."},{"label":"REQ 2 is best met by:","hint":"Irreversible, format-preserving fake data for test.","options":["Static data masking","Tokenization","Encryption"],"answer":0,"explain":"Static data masking is correct: it permanently replaces real values with realistic, non-recoverable substitutes for non-production use. Tokenization is wrong because tokens are reversible via the vault, which this requirement forbids. Encryption is wrong — encrypted data is reversible with the key, again not meeting the irreversibility requirement."},{"label":"REQ 3 is best met by:","hint":"Reversible with the key; protects data at rest.","options":["Hashing","Encryption","Masking"],"answer":1,"explain":"Encryption is correct: it protects data at rest and is reversible only with the key. Hashing is wrong because it is one-way and cannot produce plaintext. Masking is wrong — masking is not designed as a reversible, key-controlled confidentiality control for live data."},{"label":"REQ 4 is best met by:","hint":"Fixed-length, one-way fingerprint for integrity.","options":["Encryption","Hashing","Tokenization"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hashing is correct: a one-way fixed-length digest verifies integrity and cannot be reversed to the original. Encryption is wrong because it is reversible and variable in relationship to plaintext, not an integrity fingerprint. Tokenization is wrong — tokens are reversible and are for confidentiality/scope reduction, not integrity checking."}],"summary":"Tokenization = reversible vault-mapped surrogate (PCI scope); static masking = irreversible fake test data; encryption = key-reversible confidentiality; hashing = one-way integrity fingerprint."},{"id":"PBQ-09","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2.5","title":"Classify and Label Cloud Data","brief":"Apply the classification policy below to incoming data assets and choose the correct label and handling.","exhibitTitle":"CLASSIFICATION POLICY (excerpt)","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>PUBLIC</span>        No harm if disclosed. No encryption mandate.\n<span class='cy'>INTERNAL</span>      Business-only. Encrypt in transit.\n<span class='cy'>CONFIDENTIAL</span>  PII/financial. Encrypt at rest + in transit;\n              access on need-to-know.\n<span class='cy'>RESTRICTED</span>    Regulated (PHI/cardholder). Encrypt + tokenize;\n              strict access + full audit logging.\n\nINCOMING ASSETS:\n  <span class='hl'>A1</span>  Published marketing brochure PDF\n  <span class='hl'>A2</span>  Customer PII table (names, addresses, emails)\n  <span class='hl'>A3</span>  Cardholder data (PAN) for payment processing\n  <span class='hl'>A4</span>  Internal org chart, employees only","fields":[{"label":"Asset A1 (marketing brochure) should be labeled:","hint":"Intended for public release.","options":["Public","Internal","Confidential"],"answer":0,"explain":"Public is correct: a published brochure causes no harm if disclosed and needs no encryption mandate. Internal is wrong because the material is intended for public release, not business-only. Confidential is wrong — there is no PII or financial data involved."},{"label":"Asset A2 (customer PII table) should be labeled:","hint":"PII, but not regulated cardholder/PHI.","options":["Internal","Confidential","Restricted"],"answer":1,"explain":"Confidential is correct: PII maps to Confidential — encrypt at rest and in transit, need-to-know access. Internal is wrong because Internal does not mandate at-rest encryption required for PII. Restricted is wrong — Restricted is reserved for regulated PHI/cardholder data, which this is not."},{"label":"Asset A3 (cardholder PAN) should be labeled:","hint":"Regulated cardholder data.","options":["Confidential","Restricted","Internal"],"answer":1,"explain":"Restricted is correct: cardholder data is regulated and requires encryption plus tokenization, strict access, and full audit logging. Confidential is wrong because it lacks the tokenization and full-audit requirements the policy assigns to regulated data. Internal is wrong — cardholder data far exceeds business-only handling."},{"label":"Asset A4 (internal-only org chart) should be labeled:","hint":"Business-only, no PII/financial.","options":["Public","Internal","Restricted"],"answer":1,"explain":"Internal is correct: an employees-only org chart is business-only with encrypt-in-transit handling. Public is wrong because it is not intended for outside disclosure. Restricted is wrong — it contains no regulated PHI or cardholder data."}],"summary":"Match sensitivity to the policy tier: public brochure=Public, PII=Confidential, cardholder PAN=Restricted (tokenize + audit), internal org chart=Internal."},{"id":"PBQ-10","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2.7","title":"Choose the Right Retention / Deletion Action","brief":"For each records-management situation, select the correct data-lifecycle action under the retention and deletion policy.","exhibitTitle":"RECORDS EVENTS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>EVENT 1</span>  Litigation is reasonably anticipated; relevant\n          records must be <span class='hl'>preserved and exempt from routine\n          deletion</span> until released.\n\n<span class='cy'>EVENT 2</span>  Data in multi-tenant cloud storage has reached\n          end of retention; media cannot be physically\n          destroyed by the tenant. Keys are customer-held.\n\n<span class='cy'>EVENT 3</span>  Active records still within their retention window\n          but rarely accessed should move to cheaper\n          <span class='hl'>long-term cold</span> storage.\n\n<span class='cy'>EVENT 4</span>  A regulator asks how the tenant proves that a\n          specific record set was destroyed on schedule.","fields":[{"label":"EVENT 1 requires:","hint":"Preserve, suspend routine deletion.","options":["Legal hold","Crypto-shredding","Archiving"],"answer":0,"explain":"Legal hold is correct: anticipated litigation requires preserving relevant records and suspending routine deletion until released. Crypto-shredding is wrong — destroying data under a hold could be spoliation. Archiving is wrong because moving to cold storage does not create the preservation/deletion-suspension obligation a legal hold does."},{"label":"EVENT 2 is best handled by:","hint":"Tenant can't destroy media, but holds the keys.","options":["Physical shredding of drives","Crypto-shredding (destroy the keys)","Degaussing the array"],"answer":1,"explain":"Crypto-shredding is correct: destroying the customer-held keys renders multi-tenant data unrecoverable without touching shared physical media. Physical shredding is wrong because a tenant cannot destroy provider-owned, multi-tenant drives. Degaussing is wrong — tenants have no physical access to the storage array to degauss it."},{"label":"EVENT 3 is the lifecycle action:","hint":"Move rarely used, still-retained data to cheaper cold tier.","options":["Destroy","Archive","Legal hold"],"answer":1,"explain":"Archive is correct: moving still-retained but rarely accessed data to cheaper cold storage is archiving. Destroy is wrong because the records are still within their retention window. Legal hold is wrong — there is no litigation trigger, only cost optimization."},{"label":"EVENT 4 is satisfied primarily by:","hint":"Proving destruction happened on schedule.","options":["A destruction certificate / audit log of the deletion event","Re-encrypting the data","Extending the retention period"],"answer":0,"explain":"A destruction certificate / audit log is correct: auditable evidence of the destruction event proves the record set was destroyed on schedule. Re-encrypting is wrong because it does not evidence destruction. Extending retention is wrong — it contradicts the requirement to prove timely destruction."}],"summary":"Legal hold preserves under litigation; crypto-shredding destroys multi-tenant data via key destruction; archiving is cheap cold retention within window; audited destruction records prove disposal."},{"id":"PBQ-11","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2.3","title":"Design Key Management for Cloud Encryption","brief":"An architect is configuring encryption and key management for a Confidential dataset. Choose the best option for each control.","exhibitTitle":"KEY-MANAGEMENT CONFIG","exhibit":"GOAL: encrypt Confidential data so the <span class='hl'>provider cannot\n      read plaintext</span>, with strong key protection and rotation.\n\n<span class='cy'>CTRL 1</span>  Where should the customer-controlled master keys live?\n<span class='cy'>CTRL 2</span>  Model where the CUSTOMER supplies/holds keys the\n          provider uses but cannot export.\n<span class='cy'>CTRL 3</span>  Handling of application secrets/API credentials.\n<span class='cy'>CTRL 4</span>  Reducing exposure of a long-lived key over time.\n\n<span class='dim'>Concepts: HSM, BYOK/HYOK, secrets manager, key rotation, hardcoding</span>","fields":[{"label":"CTRL 1 — customer-controlled master keys are best stored in:","hint":"Tamper-resistant hardware key store.","options":["A hardware security module (HSM)","A plaintext config file","The application source repo"],"answer":0,"explain":"An HSM is correct: a tamper-resistant hardware module is the standard secure store for master keys. A plaintext config file is wrong because keys would be exposed to anyone reading the file. The source repo is wrong — committing keys to code is a classic secret-sprawl vulnerability."},{"label":"CTRL 2 — the model where the customer supplies keys the provider uses but cannot fully export is:","hint":"Customer retains ultimate key custody.","options":["Provider-managed keys only","BYOK / HYOK (customer-held keys)","No encryption keys at all"],"answer":1,"explain":"BYOK/HYOK is correct: the customer supplies and retains custody of keys, keeping the provider out of plaintext. Provider-managed keys only is wrong because then the provider controls the keys and could access plaintext. 'No keys at all' is wrong — that abandons encryption entirely."},{"label":"CTRL 3 — application secrets and API credentials should be handled via:","hint":"Centralized, access-controlled secret storage.","options":["Hardcoding them in the app","A managed secrets manager / vault","Emailing them to developers"],"answer":1,"explain":"A managed secrets manager/vault is correct: it centralizes secrets with access control, rotation, and auditing. Hardcoding is wrong because it exposes credentials in code and images. Emailing secrets is wrong — it leaks credentials into uncontrolled channels."},{"label":"CTRL 4 — exposure of a long-lived key is best reduced by:","hint":"Limit the window any single key is valid.","options":["Never changing the key","Regular key rotation","Publishing the key policy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Regular key rotation is correct: rotating keys limits the amount of data and time any single key protects, shrinking exposure. Never changing the key is wrong because a compromised key would expose everything indefinitely. Publishing the key policy is wrong — documentation does not reduce a key's exposure window."}],"summary":"Store master keys in an HSM, use BYOK/HYOK to keep the provider out of plaintext, keep app secrets in a vault, and rotate keys regularly to limit exposure."},{"id":"PBQ-12","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2.1","title":"Trace Data Flow and Dispersion Risk","brief":"A dataset is written to a distributed cloud store. Identify the concept behind each observation and its security implication.","exhibitTitle":"STORAGE TELEMETRY","exhibit":"OBJECT WRITE: customer.db backup (2.1 GB)\n\n<span class='cy'>OBS 1</span>  The object is <span class='hl'>split into chunks and spread across\n        multiple nodes and availability zones</span> for durability.\n<span class='cy'>OBS 2</span>  Some chunks physically land in a <span class='hl'>different country</span>\n        than the customer's home jurisdiction.\n<span class='cy'>OBS 3</span>  A DLP engine must know WHERE regulated fields are\n        before it can enforce policy on the flow.\n<span class='cy'>OBS 4</span>  Two tenants share the same physical storage array\n        with only logical separation.","fields":[{"label":"OBS 1 describes:","hint":"Chunked and spread for durability.","options":["Data dispersion","Data masking","Legal hold"],"answer":0,"explain":"Data dispersion is correct: splitting data into chunks spread across nodes/zones for durability is data dispersion. Data masking is wrong because no values are being obfuscated. Legal hold is wrong — nothing is being preserved for litigation."},{"label":"OBS 2 primarily raises which concern?","hint":"Chunks land in another country.","options":["Latency only","Data residency / jurisdiction","Key rotation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Data residency/jurisdiction is correct: data physically stored in another country can trigger conflicting laws and sovereignty requirements. Latency only is wrong because the primary security issue is legal jurisdiction, not performance. Key rotation is wrong — cross-border placement is unrelated to rotation."},{"label":"OBS 3 requires which capability first?","hint":"Know where sensitive fields are before enforcing.","options":["Data discovery / classification","Tokenization","Backup"],"answer":0,"explain":"Data discovery/classification is correct: DLP must first discover and classify where regulated fields live before it can enforce policy. Tokenization is wrong because you cannot tokenize what you have not first located and classified. Backup is wrong — copying data does not tell DLP where sensitive fields are."},{"label":"OBS 4 describes which condition and its main risk?","hint":"Shared array, logical separation only.","options":["Multi-tenancy — isolation/data-leakage risk","Air-gapped storage","Full physical isolation"],"answer":0,"explain":"Multi-tenancy with isolation/leakage risk is correct: shared physical storage with only logical separation is multi-tenancy, whose main risk is cross-tenant leakage if isolation fails. Air-gapped storage is wrong because the array is networked and shared. Full physical isolation is wrong — the tenants share the same array, so it is logical, not physical, separation."}],"summary":"Chunk-and-spread = data dispersion; foreign placement raises residency/jurisdiction; DLP needs discovery/classification first; shared arrays are multi-tenant with cross-tenant leakage risk."},{"id":"PBQ-13","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3.3","title":"Analyze Cloud Infrastructure Risks","brief":"During a cloud risk assessment, classify each finding by the threat/vulnerability it represents.","exhibitTitle":"RISK ASSESSMENT FINDINGS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>FINDING 1</span>  A flaw lets code escape a guest VM and reach the\n           <span class='hl'>hypervisor / other tenants</span>.\n<span class='cy'>FINDING 2</span>  A tenant cannot leave a provider without costly\n           re-engineering; proprietary formats and no export.\n<span class='cy'>FINDING 3</span>  An object storage bucket is left <span class='hl'>publicly readable</span>\n           due to a mis-set access policy.\n<span class='cy'>FINDING 4</span>  Idle, forgotten VMs and orphaned snapshots persist\n           unmonitored, expanding the attack surface.\n\n<span class='dim'>Concepts: VM escape, vendor lock-in, misconfiguration, unmanaged assets/sprawl</span>","fields":[{"label":"FINDING 1 is best classified as:","hint":"Breaking out of the guest into the hypervisor.","options":["VM escape / hypervisor breakout","Vendor lock-in","Legal hold"],"answer":0,"explain":"VM escape / hypervisor breakout is correct: code breaking out of the guest to reach the hypervisor or other tenants is the classic virtualization threat. Vendor lock-in is wrong because that is a portability/contract issue, not a breakout. Legal hold is wrong — it is a records-preservation concept, unrelated."},{"label":"FINDING 2 is best classified as:","hint":"Cannot leave without costly rework.","options":["VM escape","Vendor lock-in","Misconfiguration"],"answer":1,"explain":"Vendor lock-in is correct: proprietary formats and no export path make exit costly, the definition of lock-in. VM escape is wrong because no hypervisor breakout is involved. Misconfiguration is wrong — the issue is architectural/contractual, not a mis-set control."},{"label":"FINDING 3 is best classified as:","hint":"Public bucket from a bad policy.","options":["Misconfiguration","Vendor lock-in","Elasticity"],"answer":0,"explain":"Misconfiguration is correct: a publicly readable bucket from a mis-set access policy is a misconfiguration, the leading cause of cloud data exposure. Vendor lock-in is wrong because it concerns exit costs, not exposure. Elasticity is wrong — that is a scaling characteristic, not a risk here."},{"label":"FINDING 4 is best classified as:","hint":"Forgotten VMs and orphaned snapshots.","options":["Unmanaged assets / cloud sprawl","VM escape","Data residency"],"answer":0,"explain":"Unmanaged assets / cloud sprawl is correct: idle, forgotten resources expand attack surface and evade monitoring. VM escape is wrong because nothing is breaking out of a guest. Data residency is wrong — jurisdiction is not the issue with orphaned local assets."}],"summary":"Guest-to-hypervisor breakout = VM escape; costly exit = vendor lock-in; public bucket = misconfiguration; forgotten resources = unmanaged assets / cloud sprawl."},{"id":"PBQ-14","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3.4","title":"Select the Right Security Control","brief":"For each protection objective in a cloud platform, choose the control that best addresses it.","exhibitTitle":"CONTROL SELECTION","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>OBJECTIVE 1</span>  Provide a single hardened <span class='hl'>entry point</span> for admins\n             to reach private-subnet hosts via SSH/RDP.\n<span class='cy'>OBJECTIVE 2</span>  <span class='hl'>Detect and block</span> malicious network traffic inline\n             at the perimeter of a workload.\n<span class='cy'>OBJECTIVE 3</span>  Aggregate and correlate logs from many services\n             to detect incidents.\n<span class='cy'>OBJECTIVE 4</span>  Restrict east-west traffic between VMs to only\n             the ports/sources each role needs.\n\n<span class='dim'>Controls: bastion/jump host, IPS, SIEM, network security groups (micro-segmentation)</span>","fields":[{"label":"OBJECTIVE 1 is best met by:","hint":"Single hardened admin entry point.","options":["Bastion / jump host","SIEM","Public IP on every host"],"answer":0,"explain":"Bastion / jump host is correct: a single hardened entry point funnels and audits admin access to private hosts. SIEM is wrong because it aggregates logs, it does not gate admin access. Public IPs on every host is wrong — that expands, rather than restricts, the attack surface."},{"label":"OBJECTIVE 2 is best met by:","hint":"Inline detect-and-block.","options":["IDS (detect only)","IPS (intrusion prevention)","Honeypot"],"answer":1,"explain":"IPS is correct: an intrusion prevention system inspects inline and can block malicious traffic. IDS (detect only) is wrong because it alerts but does not block. Honeypot is wrong — a honeypot lures and observes attackers, it does not block traffic to production workloads."},{"label":"OBJECTIVE 3 is best met by:","hint":"Aggregate and correlate logs.","options":["SIEM","Bastion host","WAF"],"answer":0,"explain":"SIEM is correct: it aggregates and correlates logs across services to surface incidents. Bastion host is wrong because it controls admin access, not log correlation. WAF is wrong — a web application firewall filters HTTP traffic, it is not a log-correlation platform."},{"label":"OBJECTIVE 4 is best met by:","hint":"Least-privilege east-west traffic between VMs.","options":["Network security groups / micro-segmentation","One flat network","Disabling all logging"],"answer":0,"explain":"Network security groups / micro-segmentation is correct: per-workload rules restrict east-west traffic to only what each role needs. One flat network is wrong because it allows unrestricted lateral movement. Disabling logging is wrong — it removes visibility and does nothing to restrict traffic."}],"summary":"Bastion = single hardened admin entry; IPS = inline block; SIEM = log correlation; network security groups / micro-segmentation = least-privilege east-west traffic."},{"id":"PBQ-15","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3.5","title":"Set RTO and RPO from Business Requirements","brief":"Interpret the BC/DR requirements below and choose the correct metric or design decision for each item.","exhibitTitle":"BC/DR REQUIREMENTS","exhibit":"SYSTEM: order-processing platform\n\n<span class='cy'>REQ 1</span>  Business states it can tolerate <span class='hl'>at most 15 minutes\n        of lost transactions</span> after a failure.\n<span class='cy'>REQ 2</span>  Business states the system must be <span class='hl'>back online within\n        1 hour</span> of an outage.\n<span class='cy'>REQ 3</span>  To meet the 15-minute data-loss tolerance, how often\n        must data be replicated/backed up?\n<span class='cy'>REQ 4</span>  A minor reporting system can be down for 3 days with\n        negligible impact. Its recovery priority is:\n\n<span class='dim'>Metrics: RTO, RPO, backup frequency, recovery prioritization</span>","fields":[{"label":"REQ 1 (max 15 minutes of lost data) defines the:","hint":"Tolerable data loss measured backward from the incident.","options":["RTO","RPO","MTTR"],"answer":1,"explain":"RPO is correct: Recovery Point Objective is the maximum tolerable data loss (15 minutes). RTO is wrong because RTO measures time to restore service, not data loss. MTTR is wrong — mean time to repair is an operational average, not a data-loss target."},{"label":"REQ 2 (back online within 1 hour) defines the:","hint":"How long until service is restored.","options":["RPO","RTO","SLA credit"],"answer":1,"explain":"RTO is correct: Recovery Time Objective is the maximum tolerable time to restore service (1 hour). RPO is wrong because that measures data loss, not restore time. SLA credit is wrong — that is a contractual remedy, not a recovery metric."},{"label":"REQ 3 — to meet a 15-minute RPO, replication/backup must occur:","hint":"Backup interval must be no larger than the RPO.","options":["Once per day","At least every 15 minutes (continuous/near-continuous)","Only after an outage"],"answer":1,"explain":"At least every 15 minutes is correct: the backup/replication interval must be no larger than the RPO, so near-continuous replication is needed. Once per day is wrong because it would risk up to 24 hours of loss, far exceeding the RPO. 'Only after an outage' is wrong — you cannot back up data that is already lost."},{"label":"REQ 4 — a 3-day-tolerant reporting system should be given:","hint":"Long tolerance = lower recovery priority.","options":["Highest recovery priority (tier 1)","Lower recovery priority (recover after critical systems)","No recovery plan at all"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lower recovery priority is correct: a long downtime tolerance means it is recovered after mission-critical systems. Highest priority is wrong because scarce recovery resources should go to systems with tighter RTOs. 'No recovery plan at all' is wrong — even low-priority systems are recovered eventually, just later."}],"summary":"RPO = tolerable data loss (drives backup frequency); RTO = tolerable downtime; backup interval must be ≤ RPO; low-tolerance systems get recovered before high-tolerance ones."},{"id":"PBQ-16","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3.5","title":"Choose a DR Strategy for the Budget and RTO","brief":"Match each DR posture to the strategy that fits its RTO/cost trade-off.","exhibitTitle":"DR STRATEGY OPTIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SITE A</span>  Fully replicated, always-on standby that can take\n         traffic in seconds. <span class='hl'>Lowest RTO, highest cost.</span>\n<span class='cy'>SITE B</span>  Facility with power/network and some pre-staged\n         systems; needs data restore + config before use.\n         Moderate RTO and cost.\n<span class='cy'>SITE C</span>  Empty facility with space/power only; hardware and\n         data must be installed after a disaster. <span class='hl'>Lowest cost,\n         longest RTO.</span>\n<span class='cy'>SITE D</span>  Two active regions serving live traffic simultaneously,\n         each able to absorb the other's load.\n\n<span class='dim'>Strategies: hot site, warm site, cold site, active-active</span>","fields":[{"label":"SITE A is a:","hint":"Always-on standby, seconds to cut over.","options":["Cold site","Hot site","Warm site"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hot site is correct: a fully replicated, always-on standby with near-instant cutover and the lowest RTO. Cold site is wrong because a cold site has the longest RTO. Warm site is wrong — a warm site still needs restore/config and is slower than a hot site."},{"label":"SITE B is a:","hint":"Some pre-staged systems, needs restore + config.","options":["Warm site","Hot site","Cold site"],"answer":0,"explain":"Warm site is correct: partially provisioned with pre-staged systems that need data restore and configuration, giving moderate RTO/cost. Hot site is wrong because it is fully ready with no restore needed. Cold site is wrong — a cold site has no pre-staged systems at all."},{"label":"SITE C is a:","hint":"Space and power only; longest RTO.","options":["Hot site","Warm site","Cold site"],"answer":2,"explain":"Cold site is correct: only space/power, with hardware and data installed after a disaster, giving the lowest cost and longest RTO. Hot site is wrong because it is fully ready and expensive. Warm site is wrong — a warm site already has some systems pre-staged, unlike an empty facility."},{"label":"SITE D describes:","hint":"Two live regions sharing traffic.","options":["Active-active","Cold standby","Single region only"],"answer":0,"explain":"Active-active is correct: two live regions serve traffic simultaneously and can absorb each other's load, offering the strongest resilience. Cold standby is wrong because both sites here are already live. 'Single region only' is wrong — the design explicitly spans two active regions."}],"summary":"Hot = always-on, lowest RTO/highest cost; warm = pre-staged, moderate; cold = space/power only, cheapest/slowest; active-active = two live regions sharing load."},{"id":"PBQ-17","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3.3","title":"Choose the Risk-Treatment Decision","brief":"For each identified cloud risk, select the risk-treatment option the organization is applying.","exhibitTitle":"RISK TREATMENT REGISTER","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>RISK 1</span>  DDoS against the public API. Org buys a managed\n        <span class='hl'>DDoS-protection service</span> to reduce likelihood/impact.\n<span class='cy'>RISK 2</span>  Rare regional outage. Org <span class='hl'>purchases cyber-insurance</span>\n        to cover residual financial loss.\n<span class='cy'>RISK 3</span>  A risky beta feature exceeds appetite. Org <span class='hl'>chooses\n        not to launch it</span>.\n<span class='cy'>RISK 4</span>  A low-impact edge-case bug within appetite. Org\n        documents it and takes no further action.\n\n<span class='dim'>Treatments: mitigate, transfer, avoid, accept</span>","fields":[{"label":"RISK 1 (buy DDoS protection to reduce likelihood/impact) is:","hint":"Applying a control to lower the risk.","options":["Mitigate","Transfer","Accept"],"answer":0,"explain":"Mitigate is correct: applying a control (DDoS protection) to reduce likelihood/impact is risk mitigation. Transfer is wrong because the financial loss is not shifted to a third party, the risk itself is reduced. Accept is wrong — the org is actively acting on the risk, not accepting it as-is."},{"label":"RISK 2 (buy cyber-insurance for residual loss) is:","hint":"Shifting financial impact to a third party.","options":["Avoid","Transfer","Mitigate"],"answer":1,"explain":"Transfer is correct: insurance shifts the residual financial impact to a third party, the definition of risk transfer. Avoid is wrong because the activity continues. Mitigate is wrong — insurance does not reduce the likelihood or technical impact, it covers the loss."},{"label":"RISK 3 (decide not to launch the risky feature) is:","hint":"Eliminating the risk by not doing the activity.","options":["Accept","Avoid","Transfer"],"answer":1,"explain":"Avoid is correct: eliminating the risk by not undertaking the activity is risk avoidance. Accept is wrong because the org is not tolerating the risk, it is removing it. Transfer is wrong — no third party assumes the risk; the activity is simply cancelled."},{"label":"RISK 4 (document and take no action, within appetite) is:","hint":"Tolerating a risk that falls within appetite.","options":["Accept","Mitigate","Avoid"],"answer":0,"explain":"Accept is correct: tolerating a low-impact risk within appetite and taking no further action is risk acceptance. Mitigate is wrong because no control is applied. Avoid is wrong — the activity continues rather than being cancelled."}],"summary":"Mitigate = apply a control to reduce; transfer = shift loss to a third party (insurance); avoid = don't do the activity; accept = tolerate within appetite."},{"id":"PBQ-18","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3.4","title":"Build the Cloud Audit / Logging Pipeline","brief":"An architect is planning audit mechanisms for a cloud platform. Select the best choice for each pipeline decision.","exhibitTitle":"AUDIT PIPELINE DESIGN","exhibit":"GOAL: reliable, tamper-evident audit trail for a\n      regulated cloud workload.\n\n<span class='cy'>STEP 1</span>  Capture control-plane API calls (who did what,\n        when, from where) across all services.\n<span class='cy'>STEP 2</span>  Ensure collected logs <span class='hl'>cannot be altered or deleted</span>\n        by an attacker who compromises a host.\n<span class='cy'>STEP 3</span>  Correlate events across sources to detect an\n        incident in near-real time.\n<span class='cy'>STEP 4</span>  Keep clocks aligned so events from different\n        systems can be <span class='hl'>ordered accurately</span>.\n\n<span class='dim'>Concepts: API/audit logging, WORM/immutable + central store, SIEM correlation, time sync (NTP)</span>","fields":[{"label":"STEP 1 is best served by:","hint":"Record every control-plane API action.","options":["Control-plane / API audit logging","Disabling logs to save cost","Screenshots of the console"],"answer":0,"explain":"Control-plane / API audit logging is correct: it records who performed each API action, when, and from where. Disabling logs is wrong because it eliminates the audit trail entirely. Screenshots are wrong — they are not a reliable, queryable, complete record of API activity."},{"label":"STEP 2 is best served by:","hint":"Prevent alteration/deletion after a host is compromised.","options":["Storing logs only on the local host","WORM / immutable logs in a separate, access-controlled store","Emailing logs to an admin"],"answer":1,"explain":"WORM / immutable logs in a separate store is correct: write-once storage away from the monitored host prevents tampering even after compromise. Storing logs on the local host is wrong because an attacker who owns the host can alter them. Emailing logs is wrong — it is unreliable, incomplete, and not tamper-evident."},{"label":"STEP 3 is best served by:","hint":"Cross-source correlation, near-real time.","options":["Manual weekly log review","SIEM correlation","Deleting old logs"],"answer":1,"explain":"SIEM correlation is correct: a SIEM correlates events across sources for near-real-time detection. Manual weekly review is wrong because it is far too slow for near-real-time detection. Deleting old logs is wrong — it destroys the data needed to correlate and detect."},{"label":"STEP 4 is best served by:","hint":"Accurate event ordering across systems.","options":["Synchronized time via NTP","Letting each host keep its own clock","Removing timestamps"],"answer":0,"explain":"Synchronized time via NTP is correct: aligned clocks let events from different systems be ordered accurately for investigation. Letting each host keep its own clock is wrong because drift makes cross-system ordering unreliable. Removing timestamps is wrong — it destroys the ability to order events at all."}],"summary":"Capture API activity with audit logging, protect it with WORM/immutable central storage, correlate with a SIEM, and keep clocks aligned via NTP for accurate event ordering."},{"id":"PBQ-19","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4.3","title":"Select the Threat-Modeling Method","brief":"A cloud architect is threat-modeling a new multi-tenant SaaS billing service. Match each need to the most appropriate methodology or step.","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>THREAT-MODELING WORKSHOP — SaaS Billing Service</span>\n---------------------------------------------------\nGoal:  build a per-tenant data-flow view, then\n       classify threats and prioritize remediation.\n\nDecomposition notes:\n  * Web tier -> API gateway -> billing microservice\n  * Billing microservice -> tenant-keyed DB\n  * Shared message bus between tenants  <span class='hl'>(concern)</span>\n\nOpen questions:\n  1. Which model enumerates threats by category\n     (spoofing, tampering, repudiation, ...)?\n  2. Which model scores/ranks a found threat by\n     Damage, Reproducibility, Exploitability, ...?\n  3. Which approach is attacker/risk-centric,\n     driven by business objectives & attack sims?\n  4. First technical artifact to build before\n     any threat enumeration can begin?","exhibitTitle":"Threat-Modeling Workshop Board","fields":[{"label":"Model that enumerates threats by category (Q1)","hint":"Six-letter category mnemonic","options":["STRIDE","DREAD","PASTA"],"answer":0,"explain":"STRIDE is correct: it enumerates threats by six categories — Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information disclosure, Denial of service, Elevation of privilege — which is exactly a categorization exercise. DREAD is wrong because it is a scoring/ranking scheme for a threat already found, not an enumeration taxonomy. PASTA is wrong because it is a seven-stage risk-centric process oriented to business objectives and attack simulation, not a per-category enumeration list."},{"label":"Model that scores a threat by Damage/Reproducibility/Exploitability (Q2)","hint":"Rating/prioritization mnemonic","options":["ATASM","DREAD","STRIDE"],"answer":1,"explain":"DREAD is correct: it rates a discovered threat across Damage, Reproducibility, Exploitability, Affected users, and Discoverability to produce a priority score. ATASM (Architecture, Threats, Attack Surfaces, Mitigations) is wrong because it is a decomposition/analysis flow, not a numeric risk-rating scale. STRIDE is wrong because it classifies threat type but assigns no severity score."},{"label":"Attacker/risk-centric approach driven by business objectives (Q3)","hint":"Seven-stage simulation-driven process","options":["STRIDE","PASTA","DREAD"],"answer":1,"explain":"PASTA (Process for Attack Simulation and Threat Analysis) is correct: it is a seven-stage, risk- and attacker-centric methodology that ties technical threats back to business objectives and simulates attacks. STRIDE is wrong because it is defender/category-centric and application-scoped, not business-risk-driven. DREAD is wrong because it only ranks severity of an already-identified threat."},{"label":"First artifact to build before threat enumeration (Q4)","hint":"Where does the tenant data go?","options":["Data-flow diagram","Penetration-test report","SOC 2 attestation"],"answer":0,"explain":"A data-flow diagram (DFD) is correct: decomposing the system into a DFD with trust boundaries is the prerequisite artifact — you cannot enumerate spoofing/tampering threats without knowing the flows and boundaries. A penetration-test report is wrong because testing comes after design and validates real weaknesses rather than modeling them up front. A SOC 2 attestation is wrong because it is a third-party audit report about operating controls, not a design-phase modeling input."}],"summary":"Build the data-flow diagram first, use STRIDE to enumerate threat categories, DREAD to score/rank a given threat, and PASTA when a business-risk, attacker-centric process is needed."},{"id":"PBQ-20","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4.6","title":"Choose the Supplemental Application Security Control","brief":"An architecture review flags several exposure points in a containerized API platform. Pick the supplemental control that best addresses each one.","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>APPLICATION ARCHITECTURE — EXPOSURE REVIEW</span>\n-------------------------------------------------\n[E1] Public web app hit by SQLi / XSS payloads\n     at HTTP layer <span class='hl'>(needs L7 filtering)</span>\n\n[E2] 200+ microservice APIs need central authN,\n     rate-limiting, throttling, routing\n\n[E3] DBA cannot see who reads sensitive rows;\n     wants real-time monitoring of DB queries\n\n[E4] Legacy partner feed posts <span class='dim'>bloated XML</span>\n     with entity-expansion / schema abuse\n\n[E5] Untrusted user-uploaded code must run in an\n     isolated, resource-bounded execution context","exhibitTitle":"Exposure Review Findings","fields":[{"label":"Best control for E1 (SQLi/XSS at HTTP layer)","hint":"Layer-7 HTTP inspection","options":["WAF","Network firewall","IDS tap"],"answer":0,"explain":"A WAF (Web Application Firewall) is correct: it inspects Layer-7 HTTP/HTTPS traffic and blocks application-layer attacks such as SQL injection and XSS. A network firewall is wrong because it filters on IP/port at L3/L4 and does not parse HTTP payloads. An IDS tap is wrong because it detects and alerts but is passive and does not block the malicious request inline."},{"label":"Best control for E2 (central API authN, rate-limiting, routing)","hint":"Single entry point for many APIs","options":["API gateway","CASB","Bastion host"],"answer":0,"explain":"An API gateway is correct: it centralizes authentication, authorization, rate-limiting, throttling, and routing for many backend APIs. A CASB is wrong because it governs enterprise users' access to SaaS applications, not inbound API traffic to your own services. A bastion host is wrong because it is a hardened jump host for administrative access, not an API traffic broker."},{"label":"Best control for E3 (monitor who queries sensitive DB rows)","hint":"Watches database activity","options":["DAM","DLP","WAF"],"answer":0,"explain":"DAM (Database Activity Monitoring) is correct: it observes and records database queries in real time, giving visibility into who accessed sensitive rows. DLP is wrong because it focuses on preventing data exfiltration across channels, not fine-grained monitoring of in-database query activity. A WAF is wrong because it inspects web/HTTP traffic and never sees the SQL executed inside the database engine."},{"label":"Best control for E4 (malicious/bloated XML with entity expansion)","hint":"Parses and validates XML documents","options":["XML firewall","API gateway","Sandbox"],"answer":0,"explain":"An XML firewall is correct: it parses, validates, and filters XML documents, defeating schema abuse and entity-expansion (billion-laughs) attacks. An API gateway is wrong here because, while useful for routing/authN, it is not specialized to deep XML-schema validation and entity-expansion defense. A sandbox is wrong because it isolates code execution, not the parsing/validation of an inbound XML payload."},{"label":"Best control for E5 (run untrusted uploaded code in isolation)","hint":"Bounded, isolated execution","options":["Sandboxing","API gateway","DAM"],"answer":0,"explain":"Sandboxing is correct: it executes untrusted code in an isolated, resource-bounded environment so it cannot affect the host or other tenants. An API gateway is wrong because it mediates API traffic and does not provide a runtime isolation boundary for arbitrary code. DAM is wrong because it monitors database activity and has no role in isolating code execution."}],"summary":"Match the control to the layer: WAF for HTTP attacks, API gateway for central API governance, DAM for DB query visibility, XML firewall for XML abuse, and sandboxing for isolating untrusted code."},{"id":"PBQ-21","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4.7","title":"Design the Federated IAM Solution","brief":"A company adopts a SaaS suite and needs employees to sign in with their corporate identity. Select the correct IAM component for each requirement.","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>FEDERATED IAM DESIGN — SaaS SUITE ONBOARDING</span>\n----------------------------------------------------\nRequirements:\n  R1  Corp directory must be the authoritative\n      source that ASSERTS user identity to apps.\n  R2  One login grants access to many SaaS apps\n      without re-entering credentials.\n  R3  Web-SSO assertion format widely used for\n      enterprise browser-based federation.\n  R4  High-assurance login: password PLUS a\n      phone-based one-time factor.\n  R5  Central vault issues short-lived DB and API\n      <span class='hl'>secrets</span> to workloads, with rotation.","exhibitTitle":"Federated IAM Requirements","fields":[{"label":"R1 — authoritative source that asserts identity","hint":"The party that authenticates the user","options":["Identity Provider (IdP)","Service Provider (SP)","CASB"],"answer":0,"explain":"The Identity Provider (IdP) is correct: in federation the IdP authenticates the user and issues assertions about their identity to relying applications. The Service Provider (SP) is wrong because it is the relying application that consumes the assertion, not the party that produces it. A CASB is wrong because it is a visibility/policy broker for SaaS usage, not the identity-asserting authority."},{"label":"R2 — one login, many apps, no re-auth","hint":"Single sign-on","options":["SSO","MFA","IRM"],"answer":0,"explain":"SSO (Single Sign-On) is correct: it lets a user authenticate once and access multiple applications without re-entering credentials. MFA is wrong because it strengthens a single authentication event with extra factors, not access across many apps. IRM is wrong because Information Rights Management controls usage of documents/data, not application login."},{"label":"R3 — enterprise browser-based web-SSO assertion format","hint":"XML-based assertion standard","options":["SAML","RADIUS","SCIM"],"answer":0,"explain":"SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language) is correct: it is the XML-based assertion standard widely used for browser-based enterprise web SSO. RADIUS is wrong because it is a network access AAA protocol (VPN/Wi-Fi), not a web-SSO assertion format. SCIM is wrong because it standardizes user provisioning/deprovisioning, not the sign-in assertion itself."},{"label":"R4 — password PLUS phone one-time factor","hint":"More than one authentication factor","options":["MFA","SSO","Federation"],"answer":0,"explain":"MFA (Multi-Factor Authentication) is correct: combining a password (something you know) with a phone-based one-time code (something you have) is multi-factor authentication. SSO is wrong because it concerns reusing one authenticated session across apps, not the number of factors. Federation is wrong because it is about trusting identity across organizations, independent of how many factors were used."},{"label":"R5 — central vault issuing short-lived rotated secrets","hint":"Not for human logins","options":["Secrets management","MFA","SSO"],"answer":0,"explain":"Secrets management is correct: a secrets vault issues, rotates, and audits short-lived credentials (DB passwords, API keys) for workloads and services. MFA is wrong because it authenticates human users with multiple factors, not machine/service secrets. SSO is wrong because it federates human logins across apps, not the programmatic distribution of application secrets."}],"summary":"The IdP asserts identity, SSO reuses one login across apps, SAML carries the browser assertion, MFA adds factors to a login, and secrets management handles machine credentials — each solves a distinct IAM need."},{"id":"PBQ-22","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4.4","title":"Pick the Right Security Testing Method","brief":"A DevSecOps pipeline needs testing gates. Choose the testing methodology that best fits each described need.","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>PIPELINE SECURITY GATES — TEST SELECTION</span>\n-------------------------------------------------\nStage / Need:\n  G1  Analyze source code WITHOUT running it,\n      early in the pipeline (shift-left).\n  G2  Attack the RUNNING app from outside with\n      no source access (like an attacker).\n  G3  Inventory third-party/open-source deps and\n      flag known-vulnerable versions & licenses.\n  G4  Instrument the app from <span class='hl'>inside</span> during\n      functional tests to observe real data flow.\n  G5  Deliberately test malicious/abuse workflows\n      the app was <span class='dim'>never meant</span> to allow.","exhibitTitle":"Pipeline Test Selection","fields":[{"label":"G1 — analyze source without executing (shift-left)","hint":"Static, white-box, on source","options":["SAST","DAST","SCA"],"answer":0,"explain":"SAST (Static Application Security Testing) is correct: it analyzes source or bytecode without executing it, ideal early/shift-left. DAST is wrong because it requires a running application and tests from the outside. SCA is wrong because it inventories dependencies rather than analyzing your own source logic for flaws."},{"label":"G2 — attack the running app with no source access","hint":"Dynamic, black-box","options":["DAST","SAST","IAST"],"answer":0,"explain":"DAST (Dynamic Application Security Testing) is correct: it black-box tests a running application from the outside, as an attacker would. SAST is wrong because it inspects static source, not the running system. IAST is wrong because it requires instrumentation inside the app (grey-box) rather than a purely external black-box attack."},{"label":"G3 — inventory dependencies, flag known-vuln versions & licenses","hint":"Composition of third-party parts","options":["SCA","SAST","DAST"],"answer":0,"explain":"SCA (Software Composition Analysis) is correct: it inventories open-source/third-party components and flags known-vulnerable versions and license risk. SAST is wrong because it examines first-party source logic, not the bill of materials. DAST is wrong because it probes runtime behavior and cannot enumerate dependency versions/licenses."},{"label":"G4 — instrument the app from inside during functional tests","hint":"Grey-box, agent inside the app","options":["IAST","SAST","SCA"],"answer":0,"explain":"IAST (Interactive Application Security Testing) is correct: it instruments the running application from the inside during functional tests, observing real data flow (grey-box). SAST is wrong because it is purely static with no runtime observation. SCA is wrong because it only analyzes component composition, not live in-app data flow."},{"label":"G5 — deliberately test workflows the app should never allow","hint":"Negative / misuse scenarios","options":["Abuse-case testing","SAST","SCA"],"answer":0,"explain":"Abuse-case testing is correct: it deliberately exercises malicious/misuse workflows the application was never intended to permit, complementing functional testing. SAST is wrong because it statically scans code and does not model attacker misuse workflows. SCA is wrong because it evaluates dependency risk, not adversarial usage scenarios."}],"summary":"SAST reads source, DAST attacks the running app, SCA inventories third-party parts, IAST instruments from inside, and abuse-case testing exercises misuse workflows — layer them across the pipeline."},{"id":"PBQ-23","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4.5","title":"Verify the Software Supply Chain","brief":"Before shipping a cloud service, the team must vet the software supply chain. Choose the correct practice for each requirement.","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SUPPLY-CHAIN ASSURANCE CHECKLIST</span>\n-------------------------------------------------\n[ ] S1  Confirm a downloaded package is exactly\n        what the publisher released (integrity).\n[ ] S2  Formally assess a third-party vendor's\n        security posture before adoption.\n[ ] S3  Enforce authN, throttling & schema checks\n        on every partner-facing <span class='hl'>API</span>.\n[ ] S4  Machine-readable inventory of every\n        component in the build (transparency).\n[ ] S5  Confirm open-source deps meet license\n        obligations & have no <span class='dim'>abandoned</span> CVEs.","exhibitTitle":"Supply-Chain Assurance Checklist","fields":[{"label":"S1 — confirm a package is exactly what was published","hint":"Cryptographic proof of integrity/origin","options":["Verify code signature / hash","Increase the CDN cache TTL","Enable auto-update"],"answer":0,"explain":"Verifying the code signature or hash is correct: comparing a cryptographic signature/checksum to the publisher's proves integrity and origin. Increasing the CDN cache TTL is wrong because caching affects delivery speed, not authenticity. Enabling auto-update is wrong because blindly pulling newer versions can actually import tampered or malicious releases without verification."},{"label":"S2 — assess a third-party vendor before adoption","hint":"Due diligence on the supplier","options":["Vendor security assessment","Add the vendor to an allowlist","Sign the SLA faster"],"answer":0,"explain":"A vendor security assessment is correct: formally evaluating the supplier's security posture (questionnaires, certifications, audits) is the core supply-chain due-diligence step. Adding the vendor to an allowlist is wrong because it grants trust without evaluating whether that trust is warranted. Signing the SLA faster is wrong because contract speed does not substitute for assessing the vendor's controls."},{"label":"S3 — enforce authN, throttling, schema checks on partner APIs","hint":"Protect the API surface","options":["API security controls / gateway","Public read-only S3 bucket","Wider CORS policy"],"answer":0,"explain":"API security controls (via an API gateway) is correct: authentication, throttling, and schema validation are exactly the protections needed on partner-facing APIs. A public read-only bucket is wrong because it exposes data rather than securing an API. A wider CORS policy is wrong because loosening cross-origin rules increases exposure instead of enforcing controls."},{"label":"S4 — machine-readable inventory of build components","hint":"Bill of materials for software","options":["SBOM","SLA","MSA"],"answer":0,"explain":"An SBOM (Software Bill of Materials) is correct: it is the machine-readable inventory of every component and version in a build, enabling transparency and rapid vulnerability response. An SLA is wrong because it defines service levels, not component inventory. An MSA is wrong because it is a master services agreement (contract terms), unrelated to a component list."},{"label":"S5 — confirm OSS license compliance and no unpatched CVEs","hint":"Vet the open-source components","options":["Validated open-source management (SCA)","Disable dependency scanning","Vendor a random fork"],"answer":0,"explain":"Validated open-source management via SCA is correct: it checks license obligations and known CVEs across open-source dependencies. Disabling dependency scanning is wrong because it removes exactly the visibility you need. Vendoring a random fork is wrong because an unvetted fork can introduce new, unmaintained vulnerabilities rather than resolving them."}],"summary":"Verify signatures for integrity, assess vendors before adoption, secure partner APIs, maintain an SBOM for transparency, and use SCA to keep open-source licensing and CVEs in check."},{"id":"PBQ-24","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4.7","title":"Broker Access to Sanctioned SaaS","brief":"Security wants visibility and control over how employees use cloud apps and where secrets live. Select the correct component for each control objective.","exhibitTitle":"SaaS Governance Control Map","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SAAS GOVERNANCE — CONTROL MAP</span>\n-------------------------------------------------\nControl objective:\n  C1  Discover shadow-IT SaaS and enforce DLP/\n      access policy between users and cloud apps.\n  C2  Let a partner org's users log in using their\n      OWN IdP (cross-domain trust).\n  C3  Modern token-based SSO for mobile & SPA\n      apps built on OAuth 2.0.\n  C4  Automatically create/disable accounts in\n      SaaS as HR status <span class='hl'>changes</span>.\n  C5  Central store so no API key is <span class='dim'>hard-coded</span>\n      in source or container images.","fields":[{"label":"C1 — visibility & policy between users and cloud apps","hint":"Cloud access broker","options":["CASB","WAF","HSM"],"answer":0,"explain":"A CASB (Cloud Access Security Broker) is correct: it sits between users and SaaS to discover shadow IT and enforce DLP and access policy. A WAF is wrong because it protects inbound web-app traffic to your own apps, not employees' outbound SaaS usage. An HSM is wrong because it is a hardware key-storage device, not an access-governance broker."},{"label":"C2 — partner users log in with their own IdP","hint":"Trust across organizations","options":["Federated identity","Local account provisioning","Shared service account"],"answer":0,"explain":"Federated identity is correct: it establishes cross-domain trust so a partner's users authenticate at their own IdP and are trusted by your service. Local account provisioning is wrong because creating separate local accounts defeats the point of trusting the partner's directory. A shared service account is wrong because sharing one credential destroys individual accountability and is a security anti-pattern."},{"label":"C3 — modern token-based SSO for mobile/SPA on OAuth 2.0","hint":"Identity layer atop OAuth 2.0","options":["OIDC","SAML","Kerberos"],"answer":0,"explain":"OIDC (OpenID Connect) is correct: it is the identity layer built on OAuth 2.0, well suited to mobile and single-page apps using tokens. SAML is wrong because it is XML/browser-POST oriented and heavier for native/SPA token flows. Kerberos is wrong because it is a ticket-based protocol for internal networks, not internet-scale SaaS SSO."},{"label":"C4 — auto create/disable SaaS accounts as HR status changes","hint":"Provisioning standard","options":["SCIM","TLS","DNSSEC"],"answer":0,"explain":"SCIM (System for Cross-domain Identity Management) is correct: it standardizes automated provisioning and deprovisioning of accounts across SaaS as identities change. TLS is wrong because it secures data in transit, not account lifecycle. DNSSEC is wrong because it authenticates DNS records and has nothing to do with user provisioning."},{"label":"C5 — central store so no API key is hard-coded","hint":"Vault for application secrets","options":["Secrets manager","CASB","IDS"],"answer":0,"explain":"A secrets manager is correct: it centrally stores and injects API keys so they are never hard-coded in source or images. A CASB is wrong because it governs user-to-SaaS access, not the storage of application secrets. An IDS is wrong because it detects intrusions and plays no role in secret storage or injection."}],"summary":"A CASB brokers SaaS usage, federation trusts partner IdPs, OIDC handles modern token SSO, SCIM automates account lifecycle, and a secrets manager keeps keys out of code — each governs a different slice of cloud identity."},{"id":"PBQ-25","format":5,"domain":6,"obj":"6.3","title":"Select the Correct Audit Report Type","brief":"A customer's procurement team is reviewing a cloud provider's assurance artifacts. Match each stakeholder need to the appropriate audit report.","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ASSURANCE ARTIFACT REQUEST — CSP REVIEW</span>\n-------------------------------------------------\nStakeholder needs:\n  N1  Auditor's opinion on controls relevant to\n      the customer's FINANCIAL reporting (ICFR).\n  N2  Detailed report on security/availability\n      controls, restricted to <span class='hl'>NDA</span> parties.\n  N3  A public, general-use seal/summary suitable\n      for a website (no sensitive detail).\n  N4  Evidence controls were designed AND operated\n      effectively over a <span class='hl'>period of time</span>.\n  N5  Point-in-time snapshot: controls suitably\n      DESIGNED as of a single <span class='dim'>date</span> only.","exhibitTitle":"CSP Assurance Artifact Request","fields":[{"label":"N1 — controls relevant to customer financial reporting","hint":"ICFR-focused report","options":["SOC 1","SOC 2","SOC 3"],"answer":0,"explain":"SOC 1 is correct: it addresses controls at a service organization relevant to the user entity's internal control over financial reporting (ICFR). SOC 2 is wrong because it covers the Trust Services Criteria (security, availability, etc.), not financial-reporting controls. SOC 3 is wrong because it is only a general-use summary and is not scoped to financial-reporting controls."},{"label":"N2 — detailed security/availability report, restricted use","hint":"Trust Services Criteria, NDA","options":["SOC 2","SOC 1","SOC 3"],"answer":0,"explain":"SOC 2 is correct: it reports in detail on Trust Services Criteria (security, availability, processing integrity, confidentiality, privacy) and is a restricted-use report shared under NDA. SOC 1 is wrong because it targets financial-reporting controls, not security/availability. SOC 3 is wrong because it is a public general-use summary lacking the detailed control testing that N2 requires."},{"label":"N3 — public general-use seal/summary for a website","hint":"Marketing-safe summary","options":["SOC 3","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 1 Type I"],"answer":0,"explain":"SOC 3 is correct: it is a general-use, publicly distributable summary report suitable for websites and marketing. SOC 2 Type II is wrong because it is a detailed, restricted-use report requiring an NDA. SOC 1 Type I is wrong because it is a restricted financial-controls report, not a public seal."},{"label":"N4 — controls designed AND operating over a period","hint":"Type covering a window of time","options":["Type II","Type I","Gap analysis"],"answer":0,"explain":"Type II is correct: it evaluates both the design and the operating effectiveness of controls over a period of time (typically 6–12 months). Type I is wrong because it only opines on design at a single point in time, with no operating-effectiveness testing. A gap analysis is wrong because it is an internal readiness comparison against a standard, not a formal attestation of operating effectiveness."},{"label":"N5 — point-in-time snapshot of control design only","hint":"Type as of a single date","options":["Type I","Type II","SOC 3"],"answer":0,"explain":"Type I is correct: it attests that controls were suitably designed as of a specific date, a point-in-time snapshot. Type II is wrong because it additionally tests operating effectiveness over a period, exceeding a point-in-time snapshot. SOC 3 is wrong because it is a report distribution category (general use), not the design-vs-operating (Type I/II) distinction."}],"summary":"SOC 1 covers financial-reporting controls, SOC 2 the Trust Services Criteria under NDA, and SOC 3 is public; Type I attests design at a point in time while Type II proves operating effectiveness over a period."},{"id":"PBQ-26","format":5,"domain":6,"obj":"6.2","title":"Map the Privacy Regime and Data Type","brief":"A multinational SaaS processes personal data across regions. Identify the correct privacy framework, data type, or requirement for each scenario.","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>PRIVACY MAPPING — MULTINATIONAL SaaS</span>\n-------------------------------------------------\nScenario:\n  P1  EU residents' personal data; requires lawful\n      basis, DSAR handling, breach notice <=72h.\n  P2  US patient health records handled by a\n      cloud <span class='hl'>business associate</span>.\n  P3  Formal process to evaluate privacy risk of\n      a NEW processing activity before launch.\n  P4  ISO standard of controls for protecting PII\n      in PUBLIC-cloud processors.\n  P5  Payment card data — governed by an industry\n      <span class='dim'>contractual</span> mandate, not a national law.","exhibitTitle":"Multinational Privacy Mapping","fields":[{"label":"P1 — EU residents, lawful basis, 72h breach notice","hint":"EU privacy regulation","options":["GDPR","HIPAA","GLBA"],"answer":0,"explain":"GDPR is correct: it governs EU residents' personal data, mandates a lawful basis, data-subject access rights, and 72-hour breach notification. HIPAA is wrong because it is a US healthcare privacy law, not an EU-wide regime. GLBA is wrong because it governs US financial institutions' handling of consumer financial data, not EU personal data."},{"label":"P2 — US patient health records via a cloud vendor","hint":"US health-privacy law + covered data","options":["HIPAA / PHI","GDPR / PII","PCI DSS / CHD"],"answer":0,"explain":"HIPAA / PHI is correct: US patient health records are Protected Health Information under HIPAA, and a cloud vendor handling them is a business associate. GDPR / PII is wrong because GDPR is the EU regime, not the US health-specific law referenced here. PCI DSS / CHD is wrong because that governs cardholder data, not medical records."},{"label":"P3 — evaluate privacy risk of a new processing activity","hint":"Privacy risk assessment artifact","options":["Privacy Impact Assessment (PIA)","SOC 2 Type II","Business Impact Analysis (BIA)"],"answer":0,"explain":"A Privacy Impact Assessment (PIA) is correct: it systematically evaluates the privacy risks of a new or changed processing activity before launch. A SOC 2 Type II is wrong because it is a third-party controls attestation, not a forward-looking privacy risk assessment. A BIA is wrong because it assesses the operational/financial impact of disruptions, not privacy risk of processing personal data."},{"label":"P4 — ISO controls for protecting PII in public-cloud processors","hint":"PII-in-cloud code of practice","options":["ISO/IEC 27018","ISO/IEC 27017","ISO/IEC 27050"],"answer":0,"explain":"ISO/IEC 27018 is correct: it is the code of practice for protecting PII in public-cloud environments acting as processors. ISO/IEC 27017 is wrong because it covers cloud security controls generally, not PII protection specifically. ISO/IEC 27050 is wrong because it addresses electronic discovery, not PII protection."},{"label":"P5 — payment card data under an industry contractual mandate","hint":"Card-industry standard","options":["PCI DSS","GDPR","SOX"],"answer":0,"explain":"PCI DSS is correct: it is the payment-card industry's contractual security standard for cardholder data, enforced by the card brands rather than a national statute. GDPR is wrong because it is a data-protection law for EU personal data, not a card-industry mandate. SOX is wrong because it governs US public-company financial reporting, not payment card data."}],"summary":"GDPR governs EU personal data, HIPAA protects US PHI, a PIA assesses new-processing risk, ISO/IEC 27018 protects PII in public cloud, and PCI DSS is the card industry's contractual mandate — match the regime to the data and geography."},{"id":"PBQ-27","format":5,"domain":6,"obj":"6.4","title":"Assign Data-Protection Roles","brief":"A shared-responsibility review must classify each party by its privacy/data-protection role. Choose the correct role for each description.","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>DATA-PROTECTION ROLE ASSIGNMENT</span>\n-------------------------------------------------\nParty / description:\n  D1  The organization that determines the PURPOSES\n      and MEANS of processing personal data.\n  D2  The cloud provider that processes personal\n      data ONLY on the customer's <span class='hl'>instructions</span>.\n  D3  The individual whose personal data is being\n      processed (holds the rights).\n  D4  Internal role accountable for a data set's\n      classification & handling (business owner).\n  D5  Party with day-to-day <span class='dim'>technical</span> care of data\n      (storage, backup) but not decision authority.","exhibitTitle":"Data-Protection Role Assignment","fields":[{"label":"D1 — determines purposes and means of processing","hint":"Decides why and how","options":["Data controller","Data processor","Data subject"],"answer":0,"explain":"The data controller is correct: it is the party that determines the purposes and means of processing personal data and bears primary accountability. A data processor is wrong because it acts only on the controller's instructions and does not set purposes. A data subject is wrong because that is the individual the data is about, not a decision-maker over processing."},{"label":"D2 — CSP processes only on customer instructions","hint":"Acts for the controller","options":["Data processor","Data controller","Data owner"],"answer":0,"explain":"The data processor is correct: a cloud provider that processes personal data solely on the customer's documented instructions is the processor. A data controller is wrong because that party sets the purposes/means, which the CSP does not. A data owner is wrong because ownership/accountability for the data remains with the customer, not the CSP acting on instructions."},{"label":"D3 — individual whose data is processed","hint":"Holds the privacy rights","options":["Data subject","Data custodian","Data processor"],"answer":0,"explain":"The data subject is correct: it is the identified/identifiable individual whose personal data is processed and who holds rights (access, erasure, etc.). A data custodian is wrong because that is the technical caretaker of data, not the person the data describes. A data processor is wrong because that is an organization acting on the controller's instructions, not the individual."},{"label":"D4 — internal role accountable for classification/handling","hint":"Business owner of the data","options":["Data owner","Data custodian","Data subject"],"answer":0,"explain":"The data owner is correct: this business role is accountable for a data set's classification and handling decisions. A data custodian is wrong because the custodian implements protections but does not own classification decisions. A data subject is wrong because that is the individual the data concerns, with no internal-accountability role."},{"label":"D5 — day-to-day technical care without decision authority","hint":"Implements, does not decide","options":["Data custodian","Data owner","Data controller"],"answer":0,"explain":"The data custodian is correct: it has hands-on technical responsibility (storage, backup, access enforcement) while decision authority rests elsewhere. A data owner is wrong because the owner sets classification and handling policy rather than performing day-to-day technical care. A data controller is wrong because the controller determines purposes/means of processing, a governance role, not the technical caretaker."}],"summary":"The controller decides purposes/means, the processor acts on instructions, the data subject is the individual, the owner is accountable for classification, and the custodian provides hands-on technical care — distinct roles that must not be conflated."},{"id":"PBQ-28","format":5,"domain":6,"obj":"6.4","title":"Choose the Risk Treatment","brief":"A cloud risk register lists identified risks with proposed responses. Select the correct risk-treatment category for each response.","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>CLOUD RISK REGISTER — TREATMENT DECISIONS</span>\n-------------------------------------------------\nRisk / proposed response:\n  T1  Ransomware risk -> buy cyber-insurance so a\n      third party bears the financial loss.\n  T2  DDoS risk -> deploy a scrubbing service and\n      rate-limiting to <span class='hl'>reduce</span> likelihood/impact.\n  T3  Legacy risky feature -> discontinue it so the\n      risk no longer exists at all.\n  T4  Low-impact residual risk within tolerance ->\n      document and take <span class='dim'>no further</span> action.\n  T5  Split risk with a partner via a joint-venture\n      contract that <span class='hl'>shares</span> exposure.","exhibitTitle":"Risk Register Treatment Decisions","fields":[{"label":"T1 — buy cyber-insurance so a third party bears loss","hint":"Shift financial impact to another party","options":["Transfer","Mitigate","Accept"],"answer":0,"explain":"Transfer is correct: purchasing insurance shifts the financial consequence of the risk to a third party. Mitigate is wrong because insurance does not reduce the likelihood or technical impact of the ransomware event itself. Accept is wrong because you are actively moving the loss elsewhere rather than simply retaining it."},{"label":"T2 — scrubbing service and rate-limiting to reduce risk","hint":"Reduce likelihood/impact","options":["Mitigate","Transfer","Avoid"],"answer":0,"explain":"Mitigate is correct: adding controls that lower the likelihood or impact of the DDoS is risk mitigation (reduction). Transfer is wrong because no financial or contractual shift to a third party occurs. Avoid is wrong because the risky activity (running the service) continues; you are reducing, not eliminating, the exposure."},{"label":"T3 — discontinue the feature so the risk ceases to exist","hint":"Eliminate the activity entirely","options":["Avoid","Accept","Transfer"],"answer":0,"explain":"Avoid is correct: discontinuing the activity removes the exposure entirely, which is risk avoidance. Accept is wrong because acceptance means retaining the risk, not eliminating it. Transfer is wrong because no third party assumes the risk; the activity simply ends."},{"label":"T4 — document low residual risk and take no further action","hint":"Retain within tolerance","options":["Accept","Mitigate","Avoid"],"answer":0,"explain":"Accept is correct: when residual risk is within tolerance, the organization formally documents and retains it. Mitigate is wrong because no additional controls are being applied. Avoid is wrong because the activity is not being discontinued; the risk is knowingly retained."},{"label":"T5 — split exposure with a partner via joint venture","hint":"Distribute exposure across parties","options":["Share","Avoid","Accept"],"answer":0,"explain":"Share is correct: distributing risk across multiple parties (e.g., a joint venture) is risk sharing, a distinct treatment from wholesale transfer. Avoid is wrong because the risky activity still proceeds. Accept is wrong because the organization is deliberately spreading the exposure rather than retaining it alone."}],"summary":"Transfer shifts loss to a third party (insurance), mitigate reduces likelihood/impact, avoid eliminates the activity, accept retains residual risk within tolerance, and share distributes exposure across parties."},{"id":"PBQ-29","format":5,"domain":6,"obj":"6.5","title":"Build the Cloud Contract and Vendor Terms","brief":"Legal and procurement are drafting a cloud services agreement. Select the correct contractual instrument or clause for each requirement.","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>CLOUD CONTRACT PACKAGE — CLAUSE SELECTION</span>\n-------------------------------------------------\nRequirement:\n  V1  Define measurable uptime & support targets\n      with penalties for breach.\n  V2  Overarching legal terms (liability, IP,\n      indemnity) that <span class='hl'>govern all</span> future work.\n  V3  Scope, deliverables & timeline for one\n      specific engagement.\n  V4  Guarantee access to source code if the\n      vendor goes <span class='hl'>bankrupt</span> (viability).\n  V5  Customer's right to independently audit the\n      provider's <span class='dim'>controls</span> during the term.","exhibitTitle":"Cloud Contract Clause Selection","fields":[{"label":"V1 — measurable uptime/support targets with penalties","hint":"Service-level commitment","options":["SLA","MSA","SOW"],"answer":0,"explain":"An SLA (Service Level Agreement) is correct: it defines measurable performance targets (uptime, response times) and remedies/penalties for missing them. An MSA is wrong because it sets overarching legal terms, not the specific measurable service metrics. An SOW is wrong because it scopes deliverables for an engagement, not ongoing service-level metrics."},{"label":"V2 — overarching legal terms governing all future work","hint":"Master framework contract","options":["MSA","SOW","SLA"],"answer":0,"explain":"An MSA (Master Services Agreement) is correct: it establishes overarching legal terms (liability, IP, indemnity) that govern all subsequent engagements. An SOW is wrong because it covers a single engagement's scope under the MSA umbrella. An SLA is wrong because it addresses service performance metrics, not the master legal framework."},{"label":"V3 — scope, deliverables and timeline for one engagement","hint":"Per-project statement","options":["SOW","MSA","SLA"],"answer":0,"explain":"An SOW (Statement of Work) is correct: it defines the scope, deliverables, and timeline for one specific engagement, typically executed under an MSA. An MSA is wrong because it is the master framework, not the per-project detail. An SLA is wrong because it specifies service-level metrics, not engagement scope."},{"label":"V4 — access to source code if the vendor goes bankrupt","hint":"Third-party holds the code","options":["Source-code escrow","Right-to-audit clause","Cyber-insurance rider"],"answer":0,"explain":"Source-code escrow is correct: a neutral third party holds the source and releases it on defined triggers such as vendor bankruptcy, protecting viability. A right-to-audit clause is wrong because it grants inspection of controls, not access to code on insolvency. A cyber-insurance rider is wrong because it covers financial loss, not continuity of the software itself."},{"label":"V5 — customer's right to independently audit the provider","hint":"Inspection right in the contract","options":["Right-to-audit clause","Escrow agreement","Termination for convenience"],"answer":0,"explain":"A right-to-audit clause is correct: it contractually grants the customer the ability to audit or assess the provider's controls during the term. An escrow agreement is wrong because it deals with source-code release on triggers, not audit rights. Termination for convenience is wrong because it lets a party exit the contract, not inspect the provider's controls."}],"summary":"The SLA sets measurable service metrics, the MSA is the master legal framework, the SOW scopes each engagement, source-code escrow protects viability, and a right-to-audit clause preserves the customer's inspection rights."},{"id":"PBQ-30","format":5,"domain":6,"obj":"6.1","title":"Handle eDiscovery and Legal Requirements","brief":"A cloud-hosted service is served with litigation. Select the correct legal/eDiscovery concept for each requirement.","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>LITIGATION RESPONSE — eDISCOVERY CHECKLIST</span>\n-------------------------------------------------\nRequirement:\n  L1  Immediately SUSPEND deletion/rotation of\n      data relevant to the matter.\n  L2  ISO standard providing guidance for\n      electronic <span class='hl'>discovery</span> in the cloud.\n  L3  Documented, unbroken record of who handled\n      evidence and when.\n  L4  Assurance that a party cannot <span class='hl'>deny</span> having\n      performed a logged action.\n  L5  Risk that data in multiple countries triggers\n      <span class='dim'>conflicting</span> legal obligations.","exhibitTitle":"Litigation eDiscovery Checklist","fields":[{"label":"L1 — suspend deletion/rotation of relevant data","hint":"Preservation obligation","options":["Legal hold","Crypto-shredding","Data minimization"],"answer":0,"explain":"A legal hold is correct: it suspends normal deletion and retention rotation to preserve data relevant to litigation. Crypto-shredding is wrong because destroying keys to erase data is the opposite of preservation and could constitute spoliation. Data minimization is wrong because reducing data holdings conflicts with the duty to preserve during a matter."},{"label":"L2 — ISO guidance for electronic discovery","hint":"eDiscovery standard number","options":["ISO/IEC 27050","ISO/IEC 27018","ISO/IEC 27017"],"answer":0,"explain":"ISO/IEC 27050 is correct: it provides guidance for electronic discovery, including governance and processes. ISO/IEC 27018 is wrong because it addresses PII protection in public cloud, not eDiscovery. ISO/IEC 27017 is wrong because it covers general cloud security controls, not electronic discovery."},{"label":"L3 — unbroken record of who handled evidence","hint":"Evidence-handling trail","options":["Chain of custody","Right-to-audit","SLA credit"],"answer":0,"explain":"Chain of custody is correct: it is the documented, unbroken record of everyone who handled evidence and when, essential for admissibility. Right-to-audit is wrong because it concerns inspecting a provider's controls, not tracking evidence handling. An SLA credit is wrong because it is a service-level remedy, unrelated to evidence integrity."},{"label":"L4 — a party cannot deny a logged action","hint":"Undeniable proof of action","options":["Non-repudiation","Anonymization","Multi-tenancy"],"answer":0,"explain":"Non-repudiation is correct: it ensures a party cannot credibly deny having performed a logged, cryptographically attributable action. Anonymization is wrong because removing identity actually prevents attribution, the opposite of what is needed. Multi-tenancy is wrong because it is an architectural sharing model, not an attribution assurance."},{"label":"L5 — data in multiple countries triggers conflicting law","hint":"Cross-border legal conflict","options":["Conflicting international jurisdiction","Rapid elasticity","Resource pooling"],"answer":0,"explain":"Conflicting international jurisdiction is correct: data spread across countries can trigger conflicting and overlapping legal obligations, a core cloud legal risk. Rapid elasticity is wrong because it is a technical cloud characteristic (scaling), not a legal-conflict concept. Resource pooling is wrong because it describes shared multi-tenant infrastructure, not cross-border legal exposure."}],"summary":"A legal hold preserves data, ISO/IEC 27050 guides eDiscovery, chain of custody documents evidence handling, non-repudiation prevents denial of logged actions, and conflicting international jurisdiction is the cross-border legal risk to plan for."}]);
